      {
        "id": 2399172,
        "name": "Justin Wittkopf",
        "username": "Justin_Wittkopf",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/ecb155/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-04-17T18:09:10.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I was very fortunate to attend a small wine dinner at my friend Jeff Nemanick\u2019s home last weekend.  Many of you may know Jeff or at least have enjoyed reading his wine-related posts on the various forums over the past 10 years (Vinous,Parker, WB).   Jeff and I met on a trip to Napa 5 years ago and became fast friends.  He and I both have a love for Napa cabernet and over the years we have explored may areas of Napa together and enjoyed many fine bottles of Napa cabernet.  Over the past several years Jeff has increasingly been focused more on Bordeaux and is spending more of his money on those wines, and less on Napa wines, except for a few producers.  As such, whenever we get together for a dinner event, he is usually opening fantastic, aged Bordeaux bottles.  These are always a real treat.  For this past weekend, however, Jeff decided to go back to his roots, so-to-speak, and explore some of the best wines Napa has produced in the last 50 years.  He had been procuring these bottles for several years with the intent of hosting a Napa Unicorn wine party on some occasion.  When he learned that Alex and Graeme MacDonald would be in NYC for business this past week, he decided this was the perfect time to host the party.  Thankfully the MacDonald brothers could fit this into their busy schedule (although they did arrive late).  Jeff hosted at his home, and one of our other friends at the event, Brennan Lothery, cooked the fantastic meal.  None of us knew the wines that were going to be poured until the event started.  Jeff enjoyed keeping them secret from us.</p>\n<p>At 6:30pm the event started.  Jeff revealed his printed menu (exactly at 6:30), including the meal and wines.  We were all blown away when we read what we would be drinking. This was a collection of wines that many feel are prime examples of the best Napa has had to offer over the last 50 years.  While many can argue which bottles from Napa can truly carry the moniker \u201cUnicorn\u201d, certainly many on this list would be candidates for \u201cUnicorn\u201d status.</p>\n<p>Before I get to the wines, I must describe the incredible meal Brennan put together for us.  He put so much time and money into this meal and it showed.  All of it was terrific.  We started with Siberian Baerii Caviar with Creme Fraiche, Jamon Serrano Ham, and some cheeses.  Although not a Napa wine, Jeff opened 2 bottles of Champagne to go with these items.  Everything was amazing, especially the Caviar, and enough of it to feed an army, it seemed.  The rest of the dinner is listed below, with the wine notes to follow:</p>\n<p>Potato Leek Soup<br>\nDouble Lamb Chop over Cannelloni and Cranderry Beans with a Lamb Reduction sauce<br>\nKale Salad with red onions and walnuts<br>\nBroadbent Maple-smoked Bacon<br>\nWhite Truffle Butter basted 60-day dry-aged Bone-in Ribeye Steak, with a Wild Morrel, Black Trumpet, Oyster    and Shiitake  Mushroom Gratin<br>\nMilk Bar Crack Pie</p>\n<p><span class=\"bbcode-u\"><strong>Jacques Selosse Substance Blanc de Blancs September 2013 Disgorgement</strong></span><br>\nMy first time with this wine and is was fabulous.  Elegant, delicate, ethereal with soft subtle aromas.  Almost felt regal.  94-95 points</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">1969 Chappellet Cabernet Sauvignon</span></strong><br>\nI had never heard of this wine\u2019s history, apparently one of the true unicorns.  Both Jeff and Graeme knew the history very well.  Phillip Togni was the winemaker of this.  As the story goes the fermentation temperature got too high and Phillip feared the fermentation temperature would kill the yeast shutting down fermentation, but apparently he got lucky and that didn\u2019t happen.  The high temperature fermentation, often used today by some high-end winemakers under temperature-controlled circumstances, was unheard of at the time.  Apparently Phillip attributes that phenomenon as one of the \u201cdumb-lucky\u201d events that led to the production of this phenomenal wine.</p>\n<p>This was gorgeous out of the gate with huge dark fruit filled nose of blackberry and cassis, leather, and hints of fennel.  This smelled so young!  On the palate, the tannins were at first quite gripping, slightly overwhelming the balance of the palate to me, initially, but this smoothed out after 20 minutes or so.  Lively acidity still present making this just a glorious mouthfeel.  Astonishing wine!  After 20 minutes, easy 100 points.</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">1974 Heitz Cabernet Sauvignon Martha\u2019s Vineyard</span></strong><br>\nI wasn\u2019t sure I\u2019d ever get a chance to try this wine in my lifetime.  Jeff had another bottle of this in the waiting in case this wasn\u2019t a good bottle.  No need for that one.  This was flat out incredible.  Very seductive nose of red fruits, cedar and the often-described eucalyptus.  Very fragrant but in more of a delicate way, versus the Chappellet.  The palate was also delicate but still lively, with great grip and acidity, still with enough length to make us all sit dumbfounded for a minute after each sip.  Spellbinding wine.  100 points</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">1991 Philip Togni Vineyard Cabernet Sauvignon</span></strong><br>\nJeff reports this is the best 90\u2019s Togni.  I\u2019d never had this before, either.  The nose was a bit funky at first, but this blew off.  Very red fruited nose, almost like a cranberry element, too.  A little bell pepper note, but this was not off-putting at all, as it was almost expected.  Palate was balanced with good depth and grip.  Very nice wine.  95 points.</p>\n<p><span class=\"bbcode-u\"><strong>1994 Harlan Estate</strong></span><br>\nI haven\u2019t had too many Harlan wines.  Apparently this vintage is consistently regarded as the best of the 90\u2019s for Harlan.  The nose was much more dark than the Togni, with black and blue berry, a hint of cinnamon and cedar. The palate was light and inviting, but almost too light.  Very little tannins left here.   Didn\u2019t feel overly extracted at all, versus what some say of the 1997. Very pleasant wine.  93 points</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">1994 Bryant Family Vineyard Cabernet Sauvignon</span></strong><br>\nI think Helen Turley made this wine.  Perfumed nose of mostly red fruits and some blueberry, faint hint of cedar.  Palate was nicely balanced, but again felt almost too light.  Nice wine, but didn\u2019t blow me away.  93 points</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">1994 Colgin Cellars Cabernet Sauvignon Herb Lamb Vineyard</span></strong><br>\nHelen Turley was the winemaker for both of the Colgin\u2019s, too.  It was interesting comparing the 94 and 97 Colgin Herb Lamb\u2019s.  That wasn\u2019t the initial plan, but Jeff accidentally opened the 1994 when he was supposed to open the 1997.  So we essentially got an extra bottle of Colgin that night.  Perhaps the 1997 is mrs highly regarded than the 1994?  I don\u2019t know, to be honest.  But this was pleasant enough, but seemed a bit lacking in nose and palate.  Very light, hardly any tannins.  Red-fruited and sweet.  Pleasant wine.  92 points.</p>\n<p><span class=\"bbcode-u\"><strong>1997 Abreu Vineyards Madrona Ranch Propietary Red</strong></span><br>\nThis wine was made by Ric Forman.  Perhaps the best-regarded Abreu made by Forman.  It did not disappoint.  Gorgeous nose of black-blueberry, leather and maybe some hints of fennel.  Palate was much more enjoyable than the other 1990\u2019s wines.  Great grip and balance.  Long finish.  Great wine.  96 points.</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">1997 Colgin Cellars Cabernet Sauvignon Herb Lamb Vineyard</span></strong><br>\nTo be honest, I don\u2019t have any notes on this other than \u201csame as 1994\u201d.  I recall it having the same light feel and seemingly no tannins.  Maybe Jeff can fill in his notes.</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">2003 Scarecrow \u201cOld Men Vines\u201d Cabernet Sauvignon.</span></strong><br>\nThis was the first vintage of Scarecrow and apparently is made using only the 60-yr old vines.  Vintages after 2003 had less and less of the old vines in the mix, or so the story goes.  This was the only bottle that wasn\u2019t finished.  Very \u201cnew Napa\u201d nose of black and blueberry, sandalwood, and very spicy oak notes.  The plate was medium in feel and balance, but had these prickly tannin elements on the back palate that I associate with oak treatment.  I can see where some folks may like this, but it was not my cup of tea.  92 points.</p>\n<p><strong><span class=\"bbcode-u\">2001 Chateau d\u2019Yquem</span></strong><br>\nFlat out fantastic ways to end the night.  The was gorgeous, but still just a baby.  Love the balance and acidity these wines have.  97 points.</p>\n<p>Tremendous thanks to Jeff for opening these wines for us!  Truly a once in a lifetime experience.</p>",
